					<h2>Finding Our Space.</h2>
					<p> Going door to door is fun. You meet some amazing people, sip on a few glasses of wine, and occasionally play a hand or two. But there are downsides to all this fun. You’re not legitimate. No brick and mortar location meant no accountability. I could only take the business so far. The reputation and ability to create real change in the repair community was out of reach if I maintained mobile repairs. Plus let’s not forget the rain. It bears down on us, as though it doesn't already know the cold is going at us already, and the puddles are placed perfectly to get your pants and shoes wet. It was in February of 2009 that I decided it was time for a shop. We’ve moved from location to location since then, realizing the flaws in all, and have now settled at the historic Waterfront Station. It’s Vancouver’s transit hub, we have the Canada Line, Sky Train, and Seabus all making the station their final destination. I felt this would be the most convenient location for the majority of Vancouverites, and the neighboring suburbs.
					</p>
