					<h2>It Feels Good.</h2>
					<p> One morning, only a few days after I had formally started repairing devices I remember waking up to a phone call. "My phone" she said, in an aged voice. "It fell from my counter, its all cracked up... can you fix it?". I'm not a doctor, nor do I ever plan on being one. But I felt, what it probably feels like to be a doctor, I could help people, they had problems, dilemmas and worries, I had fixes, solutions, and a smile. I met with the women later that afternoon at a coffee shop on Davie, she left with a smile, so did I. It feels good to help, no one’s ever angry to see the guy who fixes their most beloved device. I frankly can't imagine what the life of a repo-man must be like. Life is good, when you are the good in people's lives.
					</p>
